<DOC><DOCNO> AP881212-0225 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-88 0800EST</FILEID><FIRST>a a BC-History Adv22   12-12 0498</FIRST><SECOND>BC-History, Adv22,0513</SECOND><NOTE>$adv22</NOTE><NOTE>For Release Thursday, Dec. 22</NOTE><HEAD>Today in History</HEAD><HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD><TEXT>   Today is Thursday, Dec. 22, the 357th day of 1988. There are ninedays left in the year.   Today's Highlight in History:   On Dec. 22, 1944, during the World War II Battle of the Bulge,the Germans demanded the surrender of encircled American troops atBastogne, Belgium. Brigadier General Anthony C. McAuliffe gave hisfamous one-word reply: ``Nuts!'' The Americans were able to hold outuntil additional U.S. forces ended the siege four days later.   On this date:   In 1775, a Continental naval fleet was organized in therebellious American colonies under the command of Ezek Hopkins.   In 1807, Congress passed the Embargo Act, designed to force peacebetween Britain and France by cutting off all trade with Europe.   In 1864, during the Civil War, Union General William T. Shermansent a message to President Abraham Lincoln from Georgia, saying,``I beg to present you as a Christmas gift the city of Savannah.''   In 1894, French army officer Alfred Dreyfus was convicted oftreason in a court-martial that triggered worldwide charges ofanti-Semitism. (Dreyfus was ultimately vindicated.)   In 1941, British Prime Minister Winston Churchill arrived inWashington for a wartime conference with President Franklin D.Roosevelt.   In 1963, an official 30-day mourning period for President John F.Kennedy ended.   In 1971, the United Nations General Assembly voted to ratify theelection of Kurt Waldheim to be secretary-general.   In 1977, three dozen people were killed when a 250-foot grainelevator at the Continental Grain Company plant in Westwego, La.,exploded.   In 1984, in a case that drew national attention, New York Cityresident Bernhard Goetz shot four black youths on a Manhattansubway, claiming they were about to rob him.   Ten years ago: In Guyana, a coroner's jury ruled that nearly allof the more than 900 people who died at the Peoples Temple communein Jonestown had been murdered, with the exception of two that thejury said committed suicide, and one who may or may not havecommitted suicide.   Five years ago: PLO chairman Yasser Arafat, driven into exilefrom Lebanon by Syrian-backed Palestinian rebels, stopped in Cairo,Egypt, where he received a warm welcome from President Hosni Mubarak.   One year ago: The Reagan administration criticized Israel'shandling of the Palestinian uprising in the occupied territories,particularly the military's use of live ammunition against civilians.   Today's Birthdays: Lady Bird Johnson is 76. TV personality GeneRayburn is 71. The Speaker of the U.S. House of Representatives, JimWright, is 66. Actor Hector Elizondo is 52. Baseball player SteveCarlton is 44. CBS News correspondent Diane Sawyer is 43. Baseballplayer Steve Garvey is 40. Singers Maurice and Robin Gibb are 39.Golfer Jan Stephenson is 37.   Thought for today: ``The good things in history are usually ofvery short duration, but afterwards have a decisive influence overwhat happens over long periods of time.'' _ Hannah Arendt, Americanwriter (1906-1975).</TEXT></DOC>